articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskiy said on Saturday that two more ships had passed through a "temporary" Black Sea shipping corridor established since Russia withdrew from a U.N.-backed grain export deal in July.
articles.title: Two more ships pass through Black Sea corridor -Zelenskiy

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Domestic flights were cancelled and almost 3,000 people were evacuated as Taiwan girded for the arrival of Typhoon Haikui on Sunday, which is expected to bring torrential rain and strong winds to the island's south and east.
articles.title: Typhoon Haikui prompts Taiwan to evacuate thousands, cancel flights

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Tunisian authorities placed Abdel Karim Harouni, the senior official in the opposition Ennahda Islamist Party, under house arrest, the country's main opposition coalition said on Saturday.
articles.title: Tunisia places senior official in main opposition party under house arrest

articles.author: Philip Pullella
articles.description: Calling himself one of the "humble heirs" of ancient schools of wisdom and quoting the Buddha, Pope Francis on Sunday urged all religions to live in harmony and shun ideological fundamentalism that foments violence.
articles.title: Pope, quoting Buddha, urges religious dialogue to fight fundamentalism

articles.author: Boureima Balima
articles.description: Tens of thousands of protesters gathered outside a French military base in Niger's capital Niamey on Saturday demanding that its troops leave in the wake of a military coup that has widespread popular support but which Paris refuses to recognise.
articles.title: Huge protests in Niger call for French forces to leave after coup

articles.author: Tim Cocks, Carien Du Plessis
articles.description: Like many impoverished residents of downtown Johannesburg, Sihle Dube had rented a tiny room from someone who didn't actually own it, in a rundown building that was becoming a trash-strewn haven for drugs and crime.
articles.title: Life inside the 'hijacked' Johannesburg building where scores burned alive

articles.author: Kirsty Needham
articles.description: Australia said on Sunday it would send additional police to the Solomon Islands to boost security for the Pacific Games in November, keeping them there until June to assist with a general election.
articles.title: Australia says it will send more police to Solomon Islands, extend mission

articles.author: Jeff Mason
articles.description: U.S. President Joe Biden was in northern Florida on Saturday, surveying the damage caused by Hurricane Idalia and comforting people affected by the storm, though he had no plans to meet with Ron DeSantis, the state's Republican governor and a potential presidential rival.
articles.title: Biden surveys storm damage in Florida, will not meet with DeSantis

articles.author: Wa Lone, Anna Mehler Paperny
articles.description: A deal Canada struck this year to stem the flow of asylum seekers entering from the U.S. was, at first glance, a quick success: Within days, the number of people caught at unofficial crossings along the border dwindled to a trickle.
articles.title: Canada shut its land border to asylum seekers. More refugees came anyway

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: The Nobel Foundation said on Saturday it would not after all invite the ambassadors of Russia, Belarus and Iran to attend the Nobel Prize awards ceremony in Stockholm this year, reversing an earlier decision after widespread criticism.
articles.title: Nobel Foundation cancels Russia, Belarus, Iran invites to annual prize awards
